#compdef jampack
# =============================================================================
# jampack — Georges Gomes / ‹div›RIOTS' "Static website
#           optimizer for best user experience and best Core
#           Web Vitals scores" — a Node.js CLI that takes a
#           static website build output directory and applies
#           two PASS optimizations: PASS 1 (image/asset
#           optimization with sharp/cwebp/svgo) + PASS 2
#           (gzip/brotli/zstd file compression).
#           Distinguishing from imagemin, gulp-imagemin,
#           astro-compress, and other static-site optimizers
#           by:
#             - TWO-PASS OPTIMIZATION model: PASS 1 mutates
#               HTML to use modern formats (WebP/AVIF + srcset
#               + lazy-loading); PASS 2 compresses every file
#               into .gz + .br + .zst sidecars for CDN serving
#             - WEB-VITALS-FIRST: optimizations chosen
#               specifically to improve Core Web Vitals (LCP,
#               CLS, INP, FCP) — not just raw file size
#             - DRY-RUN + REPORT MODE: --nowrite + --fail flags
#               produce machine-readable issue reports without
#               mutating files; suitable for CI quality gates
#             - GLOB INCLUDE/EXCLUDE: --include <glob> /
#               --exclude <glob> for selective processing
#             - CACHING: .jampack/cache/ stores per-file
#               processing results; --nocache disables;
#               --cleancache resets
#             - SEQUENTIAL COMPRESSION mode: --sequential_
#               compress for low-memory environments
#             - PRE-FLIGHT CHECK: refuses to run on a folder
#               that already has a _jampack/ subfolder
#               (prevents double-processing)
#             - table TABLE REPORTING: every PASS report
#               (file → original size → optimized size →
#               savings) rendered through gajus/table's JSON-
#               config TableUserConfig API
#           Used by: static site builders (Astro, Eleventy,
#           Hugo, Jekyll, Next.js SSG) needing a CDN-deploy
#           preflight optimizer; Web Vitals-focused dev teams;
#           and ‹div›RIOTS' design system + Web Components
#           workflow internally.
#
# Author:  Georges Gomes (georges-gomes on GitHub) — French
#          web standards engineer + founder of ‹div›RIOTS,
#          a London-based design-systems consultancy.  jampack
#          released 2022; active maintenance through 2026.
# Source:  https://github.com/divriots/jampack
#          https://github.com/divriots/jampack/blob/main/src/index.ts
# CLI:     src/index.ts — uses @commander-js/extra-typings
#          (commander wrapper with TypeScript inference).
#          Default subcommand `pack <dir>` + various optional
#          flags.  Headline library: **gajus/table (npm
#          package `table`)** — commander is well-documented
#          across many Node completions, table is the NEW
#          variant being documented here.
# Library: table (https://github.com/gajus/table)
#          ("table" — Gajus Kuizinas (gajus on GitHub) —
#           released 2017 as "Formats data into a string
#           table" — a JSON-CONFIG-DRIVEN Node.js table
#           renderer.  Distinct from cli-table3 (R608, the
#           Node.js Axis 10 opener), text-table, as-table,
#           easy-table, and ascii-table by being:
#             1. JSON-CONFIG-DRIVEN API — the table() function
#                takes data (array of arrays) + an OPTIONAL
#                TableUserConfig object (typed via TypeScript
#                interface) — NO instance methods, NO push(),
#                NO add_row().  Pure JSON config + functional
#                call: `const output = table(data, config)`
#             2. AJV-VALIDATED CONFIG — TableUserConfig is
#                validated at runtime via Ajv (Another JSON
#                Schema Validator) against an internal JSON
#                Schema; invalid config throws a structured
#                error pointing at the offending key
#             3. RICH BorderUserConfig — borders are configured
#                via a 17-key BorderUserConfig: topBody,
#                topJoin, topLeft, topRight, bottomBody,
#                bottomJoin, bottomLeft, bottomRight, bodyLeft,
#                bodyRight, bodyJoin, headerJoin, joinBody,
#                joinLeft, joinRight, joinJoin
#             4. STREAMING ALTERNATIVE — `createStream(config)`
#                returns a TableStream allowing row-by-row
#                emission to stdout (for streaming output to
#                terminals without buffering full data)
#             5. PER-COLUMN ColumnUserConfig — alignment +
#                width + paddingLeft + paddingRight + truncate
#                + wrapWord properties; applied per-column
#                index OR via `columnDefault` fallback
#             6. SPANNING CELLS — spanningCells: [{ col, row,
#                colSpan?, rowSpan?, alignment?, verticalAlign?
#                }] HTML-table-style cell merging
#             7. AJV-LOCKED SCHEMA — TableUserConfig schema is
#                published as a JSON Schema file so external
#                tools can validate configs without invoking
#                table itself
#             8. ESM + CommonJS dual-package with full
#                TypeScript types since v6.0)
